Cervical spinal canal stenosis: the differences between stenosis at the lower cervical and multiple segment levels. The lower cervical segments are commonly the level responsible for cervical spondylotic myelopathy however, we rarely encounter stenosis at the upper cervical segment in a clinical setting. We assumed that there might be some differences between the pathogenetic mechanisms underlying the development of cervical canal stenosis at different segments. We performed positional MRI in the weight-bearing position for 295 consecutive symptomatic patients. All subjects were classified into four groups (A: normal